summary: This FBI 302 report details the execution of a search warrant at 9 East 71st Street, New York, NY, on July 6-7, 2019, as part of the investigation into sex trafficking of minors and conspiracy. It lists the supervising agents and participants, describes the forced entry and initial contact with a housekeeper, and notes that the search was temporarily halted to obtain an amended warrant after finding evidence beyond the original scope. The report concludes with standard procedural documentation.

events.title: Search Warrant Execution at 9 East 71st Street
events.description: A federal search warrant was executed at Jeffrey Epstein's New York City residence. Law enforcement forcibly entered after no contact from occupants, found a housekeeper inside, and later halted the search to obtain an amended warrant after finding evidence beyond the original scope.

events.title: Amended Warrant Executed
events.description: The search of 9 East 71st Street resumed and was completed under an amended warrant (rider) signed by Judge Barbara Moses.

United States District Court for the Southern District of New York
keyFacts: A federal search warrant for evidence of sex trafficking of minors and conspiracy was executed at Jeffrey Epstein's New York City residence (9 East 71st St) on July 6, 2019.

The search was temporarily halted because agents found 'several items of evidentiary value in plain view that were beyond the scope of the warrant,' necessitating an amended warrant from Judge Barbara Moses.
Law enforcement forcibly entered the residence after announcing themselves and receiving no response, finding only a female housekeeper inside.
The document provides a comprehensive list of over 20 FBI agents, task force officers, and specialists who participated in the high-profile search.
Legal counsel Marc A. Fernich was provided copies of the search documents, indicating legal representation was involved for the property's interests post-search.
